  1. (5pt) Make a plot of total CO2 emissions over time for the U.S, China, and India. Add a few more countries of your choice. Explain what do you see.
miscCountries <- gapMinder %>% 
  filter(name == 'United States of America'|name == 'China' | name == 'India'| name == 'Japan' | name == 'Russian Federation')
ggplot(miscCountries) +
  geom_point(aes(x = time, y = co2, col = name))+
  ggtitle("Co2 Emissions Among Countries")+
  xlab("Year") +
  ylab("Emissions (kt)")

  1. (6pt) Compute average CO2 emissions per capita across the continents (assume region is the same as continent). Comment what do you see. Note: just compute averages over countries and ignore the fact that countries are of different size.
continents <- gapMinder %>% 
  select(time,region,co2_PC) %>% 
  na.omit() %>% 
  group_by(time,region) %>%
  summarize(n = mean(co2_PC))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'time'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
ggplot(continents) +
  geom_point(aes(x = time, y = n, col = region)) +
  ggtitle("Average co2 emissions per Capita across Continents")+
  xlab("year")+
  ylab("Mean emssions per capita (metric tons)")

I see that the Americas, and Asia wre all over the charts near the beginning, and they started to level out more so after the 90s

  1. (6pt) Compute the average life expectancy for each continent in 1960 and 2019. Do the results fit with what do you see on the figures? Note: here as average I mean just average over countries, ignore the fact that countries are of different size.
lifeExpectancyTimes <- gapMinder %>% 
  filter(time == 1960 | time == 2019) %>% 
  group_by(region,time) %>% 
  select(region,time,lifeExpectancy) %>% 
  na.omit() %>% 
  summarize(n = mean(lifeExpectancy))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'region'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
ggplot(lifeExpectancyTimes)+
  geom_col(aes(x = region, y = n, fill=factor(time)),position = "dodge") +
  ggtitle("Average Life Expectancy per Continent in 1960 and 2016")+
  xlab("Continents")+
  ylab("Mean Life Expectancy")

  1. (8pt) Compute the average LE growth from 1960-2019 across the continents. Show the results in the order of growth. Explain what do you see. Hint: these data (data in long form) is not the simplest to compute growth. But you may want to check out the lag() function. And do not forget to group data by continent when using lag(), otherwise your results will be messed up! See https://faculty.washington. edu/otoomet/info201-book/dplyr.html#dplyr-helpers-compute.
LEGrowth <- gapMinder %>% 
  filter(time == 1960| time == 2019) %>% 
  group_by(region, time) %>%
  select(region,time,lifeExpectancy) %>% 
  na.omit %>% 
  summarize(n = mean(lifeExpectancy)) %>% 
  mutate(prev = lag(n),
         growth = n - prev) %>% 
  na.omit() %>% 
  arrange(desc(growth)) %>% 
  select(region,growth)
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'region'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
LEGrowth
## # A tibble: 5  2
## # Groups:   region [5]
##   region   growth

## 2 Africa     22.6

## 5 Europe     11.1

I see that the order of the biggest growth, also that the continents that had the largest highest life expectancy increased the it seems.

  1. (6pt) Show the histogram of GDP per capita for years of 1960 and 2019. Try to put both histograms on the same graph, see how well you can do it!
gpdPerCaptia <- gapMinder %>%

ggplot(gpdPerCaptia) +

7. (6pt) What was the ranking of US in terms of life expectancy in 1960 and in 2019? (When counting from top.) Hint: check out the function rank()! Hint2: 17 for 1960.

usLifeExpectancyRank <- gapMinder %>% 
  group_by(time) %>% 
  select(name,time,lifeExpectancy) %>% 
  na.omit %>% 
  mutate(rank = rank(desc(lifeExpectancy))) %>% 
  filter(name == 'United States of America') %>% 
  select(rank,time)
ggplot(usLifeExpectancyRank)+
  geom_line(aes(x = time, y = rank)) + 
  ggtitle("US rank in Life Expectancy over time") +
  xlab("Year") +
  ylab("Rank Number")

8. (6pt) If you did this correctly, then you noticed that US ranking has been falling quite a bit. But we also have more countries in 2019what about the relative rank divided by the corresponding number of countries that have LE data in the corresponding year? Hint: 0.0904 for 1960.

usLifeRelativeExpectancyRank <- gapMinder %>% 
  group_by(time) %>% 
  select(name,time,lifeExpectancy) %>% 
  na.omit %>% 
  mutate(rank = rank(desc(lifeExpectancy))/n_distinct(name)) %>% 
  filter(name == 'United States of America') %>% 
  select(rank,time)
